l Security to religion, diversity, and immigration, the authors argue that there are sensible, centrist solutions that are more in keeping with prevailing public sentiment and that would better serve the national interest. On issue after issue, the authors show how the conventional framing of the debate in Washington has misled Americans, creating a series of false dilemmas and forcing choices between two extremes-at the expense of more balanced and pragmatic policy solutions based on enduring American values.Uniting America provides a blueprint for a fresh approach to American politics, grounded in moderation, pragmatism, and the shared values that unite Americans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aConflits sociauxxÉtats-Unis. 0aCulture politiquexÉtats-Unis. 0aDemocracyxUnited States. 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aDémocratiexÉtats-Unis. 0aPolarisation collective. 0aPolarization (Social sciences) 0aPolarization (Social sciences). 0aPolitical culturexUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aSocial conflictxUnited States. 0aSocial conflictzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aGarfinkle, Norton, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYankelovich, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133189423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300133189.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles